 Partition function 

As advertised in the introduction, there is an interesting
cancellation between contributions coming from the  terms in the
"classical" action and those coming from integrating out the
fluctuations. 

Consider for example the free theory at 
. Then from the formulation in terms of the fields  the
partition function may be exactly evaluated
  Z = N 2 [_ (p_n^2 + m_0^2)] 
Clearly this exact answer is reproduced by the  classical
value of the collective field action in . Therefore the
 contributions from  should cancel whatever one
gets by integrating out the fluctuations . This is
straightforward to check. The  contribution to the effective 
action coming from the fluctuations is given by (for )
S_1^(2)  = 12 __1,_2 
 (p__1 ^2 p__2 ^2) = M^d _ p_^2 
Adding the contribution  from  (with
 ) we see that the total 
contribution to the partition function is
( Z)_1 = -(S_1^(1)  + S_1^(2) ) = 0 
as expected.  From the collective field theory point of view, at any
stage of the  expansion, there are two contributions, one from
the "classical" action and one from the fluctuations.  For the free
theory these should cancel precisely.

For  the situation is more complicated. Here there
are nonzero subleading terms in the partition function. Now
contributions from the classical action partially  cancel those
coming from the fluctuations. Significantly, in the continuum limit
the ultraviolet divergent terms cancel at the level of leading 
correction - this is evident from the fact that at this level the
effect of a nonzero  is to simply change the mass gap, and
this does not affect the ultraviolet behavior. These cancellations
have important consequences for a holographic interpretation.

Nature of interactions 

The cubic and higher order interactions in the collective field theory
come entirely from the Jacobian factor. On the finite lattice this has
the structure
(N-2M^d)Tr [ _0 - _k=2 ^(-1)^k k N^k/2  (_0^-1 )^k] 
In each order of  there are generically two terms
which come from the two terms in the overall coefficient.

The interactions have an interesting scale invariant form in the
critical theory. In this case the classical value of the collective
field  is simply the massless propagator and it is
straightforward to see that the term which contains  factors of the
fluctuation  has the following form in the continuum and
thermodynamic limits
