Holographic correspondence 

Our proposal is that the collective field theory described above
provides a description of the singlet sector of the vector
model in terms of a  dimensional theory of higher spins.
The basic idea is to write the collective field as a function of the
center of mass coordinates  and the relative coordinate  as
in  and . One can then expand the field  as
(, ) = _l,m 
_l  (,r) Y_l  (_i) 
where we have written the  relative coordinates  in 
terms of its magntitude  and  angles 
.  denote the
spherical harmonics on . Since
the original field  is symmetric under interchange of
 and , it should be symmetric under .
This means that only even (or zero ) values of  appear in the
expansion . Thus the collective field is equivalent to
a collection of higher spin fields living in  dimensions spanned
by  and there is exactly one field for each even spin. 

Note that if we had a  rather than a  symmetry one would
have odd spins as well.

For  we thus have a four dimensional theory. When the vector
model is at one of its fixed points, the theory is conformally 
invariant and has a symmetry group . It is then natural
to expect that the four dimensional theory is defined on 
which has the same isometry. We will see later in what sense this
is true.

In the remaining part of this section we will discuss several issues
which points towards an interpretation of the collective field
theory for the fixed point models 
as a holographic  theory defined on the boundary of .

Finite temperature thermodynamics 

One of the crucial aspects of holography is that the high temperature
thermodynamics of the bulk theory in  dimensions is appropriate
to a theory in  dimensions. Furthermore, the result involves 
which is the coupling constant of the bulk theory. This leading result
cannot come from counting of the states of the bulk theory since 
appears in the latter only through the coupling constant and in a
 expansion one would expect a  answer which reflects
that the propagating modes live in  dimensions.
In known examples of holography, however, a  dependent answer
characteristic of a  dimensional theory comes from the fact that
the bulk theory is typically a theory of gravity and its high
temperatrure properties are dominated by black holes whose entropies
is proportional to their areas and whose thermodynamics is appropriate
to that of theory in  dimensions. Furthermore the black hole
entropy is a "classical" effect and 
goes as the inverse of the square of the coupling constant and
therefore contains the right power of .

In the previous section we have calculated the leading order and
the  corrections to the partition function of the collective
field theory defined on a periodic lattice with  sites in each direction.
We now use these results to discuss the finite temperature behavior.
To do this all we have to do take  large but consider different
lattice spacings in the "space" and the "euclidean time" directions.
Finally we have to consider a continuum limit and a thermodynamic
limit in which the physical extent of the euclidean time direction is
a finite quantity  
while those in the space directions are  with . 

First consider the gaussian fixed point at  in any
number of dimensions.
The finite temperature free energy may be read off from  in
a standard fashion. The expression  has a leading divergent
term which is extensive, proportional to  - the
coefficient being the ground state energy density. The next subleading
term, which we denote by , 
is proportional to  and has the form
= - N L^d-1  d^d-1  p 
(2)^d-1   (1 - e^-p ) 
This is then related to the thermodynamic free energy  by
 F = 1  It is clear that 
 F N L^d-1  T^d  
which is nothing but the free energy of  species of massless
particles in  space dimensions. In particular the entropy scales as
 S N L^d-1  T^d-1  

From the point of view of the vector model this result is of course
obvious. However, from the point of view of the collective field
theory this is a rather nontrivial result. As we saw, we can interpret
this theory as a theory of higher spin fields in  dimensions.
Naively one would expect that the thermodynamics would be the one
appropriate to , rather than , space dimensions and should
be of  as explained above. 

The point is that
all these expectations are based on the usual situation where the
leading thermodynamic free energy comes from the "one loop" 
contribution. In the present context this is the leading 
correction, which actually gives a  contribution to the free
energy. What we saw above, however, is that there is a classical 
contribution to the free energy which is proportional to  
which leads not only to a nontrivial internal energy, but a
nontrivial entropy proportional to   . 
In fact
there are no  corrections to this result for the 
theory due to the complete cancellation discussed above. For 
 the cancellation is not complete and there are finite 
corrections. However the divergent terms which contributes to the
vacuum energy cancels. The finite tempertaure behavior of the
interacting  model was discussed long time ago in
L. Dolan and R. Jackiw, Phys. Rev.  D 9  3320 
and more recently in S. Sachdev, 
Phys.Lett.  B309  285. .

The fact that the leading thermodynamics comes from the classical
contribution to the action is reminiscent of the Gibbons-Hawking
calculation of the entropy of a black hole.  As will be seen below,
the space-time interpretation of the four dimensional collective field
theory does not appear to be straightforward and it is difficult to
identify what kind of space-time configurations give rise to this
classical contribution. Nevertheless our result strongly suggests that
the four dimensional bulk theory of higher spin fields have black
holes.

Conformal transformations and  

While the fields  do represent higher spin fields
in  dimensions, they are not the standard higher spin fields as
discussed in , but related by some field redfinition.  This may
be seen from the fact that the quadratic action is not diagonal in the
spins. A spin  field mixes with spins . We do not know
what is the exact field redefinition which relates these components to
the standard fields of higher spin theories.

An important indication of this fact comes from an examination of the
transformation properties of the collective field under conformal
transformations on the boundary. Consider for example the theory at
the gaussian fixed point. 
